Another important finding of the report was the survey results highlighted that four out of five women view spousal violence as a criminal behavior that is punishable under criminal codes.
Education is perceived as one of the key factors behind knowledge of laws as most women with tertiary education support the fact that a violation of laws is punishable or not. Similar on this regard, most are in favor of education in spreading awareness of laws.
Section Two Versus Laws Analysis Two laws introduced since the Second National Report (2008) are judicial inspection and contract review (prevalence of marriage contracts with terms that violate the law). Judicial inspection investigates compulsory situations between a woman and her husband. The same law emphasizes that the husband can not withhold consent to the divorce. Women’s rights lawyers were able to apply for divorce if a woman did not want to renew the fixed-term contract marriage as a result of the investigation and the results were made available to the woman as an official document.
The introduction of the above law led to requests from many women’s rights lawyers who were making cases seeking divorce. The majority of men appealed to the law because of the cost they incurred if the woman decided against renewal, as well as police involvement to approve the continuation of the marriage.
